    <h1>BMI Is the Wrong Number <span>After 50</span></h1>
    <p class="hero-sub">It was invented by a mathematician in the 1830s. It can't tell muscle from fat. And for men over 50, it may be giving you a false sense of where you actually stand.</p>
  </header>

  <div class="article-wrap">

    <div class="quick-answer">
      <div class="quick-answer-label">Quick Answer</div>
      <ul>
        <li>BMI was created in the 1830s as a population statistics tool — not a health assessment for individuals</li>
        <li>It measures weight divided by height squared — it cannot distinguish muscle from fat</li>
        <li>Muscular men over 50 who lift regularly often register as "overweight" or "obese" despite being healthy</li>
        <li>Men losing muscle to sarcopenia can register as "normal" BMI while their body composition deteriorates</li>
        <li>For men over 50, muscle mass and protein intake are far more meaningful indicators than BMI</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <p>I'm 64. I've had doctors reference my BMI in the same breath as whether I should "watch my weight." I train consistently, I hit my protein target, and I carry more muscle than most men my age. My BMI says I'm borderline overweight. My body says otherwise.</p>

    <p>Most men asking "is BMI accurate after 50?" are actually asking the wrong question. The real question is: <em>what number should I actually be tracking?</em> BMI isn't just imprecise for older men — it's pointing in the wrong direction entirely.</p>

    <div class="author-note">
      <div class="author-avatar">R</div>
      <div>
        <p><strong>Robert, founder of SnapProtein.</strong> I'm 64 and I've been told to watch my BMI by people who didn't ask how much muscle I was carrying. This post is about what actually matters after 50 — and why the number on most health charts isn't it.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2>Where BMI Came From (This Part Matters)</h2>

    <p>BMI — Body Mass Index — was developed by Adolphe Quetelet, a Belgian mathematician, in the 1830s. Not a physician. A mathematician. He was trying to describe the statistical distribution of body weight across large populations — the kind of work that helps governments understand public health trends in aggregate.</p>

    <p>Quetelet never intended his formula to assess the health of individual people. He said as much. The index was designed to describe the average man statistically — not to evaluate whether any particular man was healthy.</p>

    <div class="bmi-origin">
      <div class="bmi-origin-label">BMI by the numbers</div>
      <div class="bmi-origin-stat">190 years <span>old</span></div>
      <p class="bmi-origin-desc">The BMI formula hasn't changed since the 1830s. It was adopted by the medical community in the 1970s as a convenient screening proxy — not because it accurately assessed individual health, but because it was simple. Weight divided by height squared. No equipment required. No distinction between muscle and fat. No adjustment for age.</p>
    </div>

    <p>For a broad population survey, this is fine. For telling a 58-year-old man who lifts three times a week whether he's healthy — it's the wrong tool entirely.</p>

    <h2>The Two Ways BMI Fails Men Over 50</h2>

    <p>The failure isn't random. For men over 50, BMI breaks down in two specific and opposite directions — and both are dangerous.</p>

    <div class="failure-cards">
      <div class="failure-card type-a">
        <div class="failure-card-label">Failure Mode A — The False Alarm</div>
        <h3>Muscular men flagged as overweight</h3>
        <p>Muscle is denser than fat. A man who lifts consistently carries more muscle mass than a sedentary man of the same height and weight — and will have a higher BMI as a result. Many fit, active men over 50 fall in the "overweight" (25–29.9) or even "obese" (30+) BMI range not because they're unhealthy, but because muscle is heavy. BMI reads this as a problem. It isn't.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="failure-card type-b">
        <div class="failure-card-label">Failure Mode B — The False Reassurance</div>
        <h3>Men losing muscle register as "normal"</h3>
        <p>This one is more dangerous. As men over 50 experience sarcopenia — the gradual loss of muscle mass — their weight often stays relatively stable because fat replaces muscle. The scale doesn't move. BMI stays "normal." But body composition is deteriorating quietly. A man in this situation gets a clean bill of health from his BMI while the tissue that determines his metabolic health, strength, and longevity is eroding. BMI misses this entirely.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="callout">The man who needs to worry isn't always the one with the high BMI. He's often the one with the "normal" BMI who hasn't lifted a weight in five years.</div>

    <h2>BMI vs. What Actually Predicts Health After 50</h2>

    <p>Research on aging and health outcomes consistently points to muscle mass — not weight, not BMI — as one of the strongest predictors of longevity, metabolic health, and functional capacity in older adults. Higher muscle mass is associated with better insulin sensitivity, lower cardiovascular risk, stronger bones, and better outcomes from illness and surgery.</p>

