    <div class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Why is BMI inaccurate for men over 50?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">BMI measures total weight relative to height — it cannot distinguish between muscle and fat. For men over 50, this creates two critical failures: muscular men who lift weights register as "overweight" despite being metabolically healthy, and men losing muscle to sarcopenia register as "normal" despite their body composition deteriorating. BMI was designed as a population-level statistical tool, not an individual health assessment.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">What should men over 50 track instead of BMI?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">For men over 50, muscle mass and daily protein intake are more meaningful indicators than BMI. Muscle mass determines metabolic rate, strength, balance, and long-term health outcomes far more than total weight. Tracking protein intake daily ensures you're feeding the tissue that matters most. Strength trend over time and waist circumference are also more useful than BMI.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">What is a healthy BMI for men over 50?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">The standard BMI categories don't account for age-related changes in body composition. Many fit, muscular men over 50 fall in the "overweight" range not because they're unhealthy, but because muscle weighs more than fat. A better question is not "what is my BMI?" but "how much of my weight is muscle, and am I maintaining it?"</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Who invented BMI and why?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">BMI was created by Adolphe Quetelet, a Belgian mathematician, in the 1830s. It was designed as a statistical tool for describing populations — not for assessing individual health. Quetelet was not a physician. The formula was adopted by the medical community in the 1970s as a convenient screening proxy despite its known limitations for individuals, particularly those with higher muscle mass or those over 50.</div>
      </div>
